Doc Spatz<br><br>
On regards to the race issue in Vietnam, talk to anyone who was in the field in Vietnam and the MAJORITY will tell you there are no racial problems in combat units.  Men have to depend on each other in combat, so there is no room for stupid, ignorant hatred based on color etc.  From talking to vets, my dad included I get the distinct impression that a majority of the racism against African Americans happened in non-field units.  Why are the opinions of the vets here?  Did any of you see racism in their units?<br><br>
In regards to Vietnamese views on Blacks, I believe there was certainly a racist tone.  In the book INSIDE THE VC AND NVA by Michael Lee Lanning and Dan Craig, the authors discuss VC/NVA propaganda in which VC and NVA political officers would tell villagers that the Americans had a machine that could turn them black.  Also, some Vietnamese look down upon Cambodians, who have darker skin colors.<br><br>
Here is my question to all:  Do you think that blacks were drafted in larger numbers to compensate for whites avoiding service?<br><br>
Charles Moskos, the famed Military Sociologists (who has testified on the women in combat unit discussions recently), co-authored a book with John Sibley Butler (a fellow Sociologist) called &quot;All That We Can Be&quot;.  He analyzed the claim that blacks were used as cannon fodder during Vietnam and reported &quot;defintely that this charge is untrue.  Black fatalities amounted to 12 percent of all Americans killed in Southeast Asia-a figure proportional to the number of blacks in the US population at the time and slightly lower than the proportion of blacks in the Army at the close of the war.&quot;<br><br>
If African Americans had higher loss percentages earlier in the war, could it be that many of these men volunteered for combat units and possibly the military (for training, education etc.)?  Instead of labeling African Americans as victims in Vietnam, I believe we should honor all of them.  When is the last time you saw a street named after a black Medal of Honor winner.  I believe we need to recognize their service instead of creating controversy. 
